            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This income tax calculator uses a progressive tax system: your
                income is split into bands (brackets), and each band is taxed at
                its own rate. The tool:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Converts your income to an annual amount (even if you enter
                  hourly, weekly, or monthly pay).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtracts deductions to estimate your
                  <strong>taxable income</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Applies the selected country’s tax brackets to each slice of
                  income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Subtracts any <strong>tax credits</strong> from the calculated
                  tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Shows your <strong>net (take‑home) pay</strong>, effective tax
                  rate, and marginal tax rate.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Progressive tax formula</h3>
              <p>
                For a set of tax brackets, each with an upper limit \(L_i\) and
                rate \(r_i\), the tax is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                For each bracket i:<br />
                <code
                  >taxable_i = max(0, min(taxableIncome, L_i) − L_{i-1})</code
                ><br />
                <code>tax_i = taxable_i × r_i</code><br /><br />
                Total tax:<br />
                <code>totalTax = Σ tax_i − taxCredits</code>
              </div>
              <p>Your <strong>effective tax rate</strong> is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <code>effectiveRate = totalTax ÷ grossIncome</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                Your <strong>marginal tax rate</strong> is simply the rate of
                the highest bracket that contains any of your taxable income.
              </p>

              <h2>Understanding the key outputs</h2>
              <h3>Gross income vs taxable income</h3>
              <p>
                <strong>Gross income</strong> is what you earn before any tax or
                deductions. <strong>Taxable income</strong> is what’s left after
                subtracting allowable deductions (retirement contributions,
                allowances, etc.).
              </p>

              <h3>Net (take‑home) pay</h3>
              <p>Net pay is the amount you keep after income tax:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <code>netPay = grossIncome − totalTax</code>
              </div>
              <p>
                Many people find it easier to plan budgets using net monthly or
                weekly pay, which this calculator shows alongside the annual
                figure.
              </p>

              <h3>Deductions vs tax credits</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Deductions</strong> reduce your taxable income before
                  tax is calculated.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tax credits</strong> reduce your tax bill after it has
                  been calculated.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For the same amount, a tax credit usually saves you more than a
                deduction, because it reduces tax dollar‑for‑dollar.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and important notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool focuses on <strong>income tax</strong> only. It does
                  not include social security, Medicare, national insurance, or
                  local/state taxes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Real‑world tax systems include many special rules, exemptions,
                  and thresholds that are not fully modeled here.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use this calculator for
                  <strong>planning and education</strong>, not as a substitute
                  for official tax software or professional advice.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For official guidance, always refer to your country’s tax
                authority or a qualified tax professional.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>What does this income tax calculator do?</h3>
              <p>
